TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bolton, Patrick
AU  - Faure-Grimaud, Antoine
T1  - Thinking Ahead: The Decision Problem
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/10/01
DO  - 10.1111/j.1467-937X.2009.00554.x
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 76
IS  - 4
SP  - 1205
EP  - 1238
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We propose a model of costly decision making based on time-costs of deliberating current and future decisions. We model an individual decision-maker's thinking process as a thought-experiment that takes time, and lets the decision maker ‘think ahead’ about future decision problems in yet unrealized states of nature. By formulating an intertemporal, state-contingent, planning problem which may involve costly deliberation in every state of nature, and by letting the decision maker deliberate ahead of the realization of a state, we attempt to capture the basic observation that individuals generally do not think through a complete action plan. Instead, individuals prioritize their thinking and leave deliberations on less important decisions to the time or event when they arise.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-937X.2009.00554.x
ER  - 



